<P>
NO GINGRICH CASE, COUNSEL SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After a three-month investigation, the outside counsel handling the ethics case 
of Rep. Newt Gingrich, the House's No. 2 Republican leader, has found no reason 
to pursue the case, congressional sources said today. 
</P>
<P>
However, the law firm hired by the House Ethics Committee did come up with a 
list of unanswered questions that the panel's staff will pursue with Gingrich 
of Georgia before a final disposition of the case is made, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
The case stems from a complaint by Rep. Bill Alexander (D-Ark.) that Gingrich 
violated House rules and federal campaign finance laws in the operation of a 
limited partnership created in 1984 to promote "Window of Opportunity," a book 
written by Gingrich and two others. 
</P>
