<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
CAL GAME IS ON -- AT BERKELEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BERKELEY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Just four days after the Bay Area was hit by a catastrophic earthquake, the 
Washington Huskies and the California Golden Bears will meet Saturday at 
Berkeley's Memorial Stadium on the Cal campus. 
</P>
<P>
The stadium at Strawberry Canyon was not damaged by Tuesday's 6.9 quake, and UC 
Chancellor Ira Heyman announced Thursday that the Washington-Cal game was 
officially on. 
</P>
<P>
The Cal stadium was designed 15 years after San Francisco's 1906 quake and was 
built with earthquakes in mind. It was constructed in sections with expansion 
joints to withstand earth movements. 
</P>
<P>
After the quake, the location of the game had been in doubt. Mike Lude, 
Washington's athletic director, called Cal Athletic Director Dave Maggard and 
offered to move the game to Husky Stadium in Seattle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
